article.description: Duke struggled, but rallied to overcome Georgia State and set a school record for wins.
article.headline: Beard's 19 points enough vs. Georgia State
article.linkText: Duke starts slow, but wins NCAA opener
article.story:
RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Duke coach Gail Goestenkors wanted her team
to give its best effort of the season Sunday.

	   It took the Blue Devils more than a half to respond.

	   Alana Beard scored 19 points and the Blue Devils set a school
record for wins but struggled to a 66-48 victory over Georgia State
in the first round of the Midwest Regional.

	   "One of our keys was to have an attack mind-set,'' Goestenkors
said. "I talked about having that mind-set on both ends of the
court. I felt like the one thing that I asked we weren't doing. We
were back on our heels a little bit.

	   "I was very upset at halftime. Our level of effort and
intensity wasn't what we've come to expect from our team.''

	   Top-seeded Duke (32-1) didn't get its first double-digit lead of
the second half until more than midway through the period against
the 16th-seeded Lady Panthers (20-11), the champions of the
Atlantic Sun Conference who had won 10 straight entering the game.

	   "We were competing and staying focused, but I couldn't help
having thoughts about how frustrating it was that we were not
playing as a 13 or 14 seed,'' Georgia State coach Lea Henry said.
"I felt like our team could have won today if we would have been
in that position.''

	   Despite the lackluster effort, Duke, which won 31 games last
year in advancing to the Final Four, moved on to play Utah in the
second round Tuesday.

	   "I know they are a pretty good motion team, a smart team, with
a great inside-outside game,'' Beard said.

	   Beard also added eight rebounds and four blocks as Duke
dominated the offensive boards 21-6 and outscored the Lady Panthers
18-2 from the foul line.

	   Duke scored a season-low 54 points in Reynolds Coliseum -- home
of the North Carolina State women -- on Jan. 29. And the Blue Devils
struggled again in this arena, where they were 8-19 all-time before
Sunday.

	   Duke, playing for the first time in 13 days, won despite
shooting 29 percent in the second half as Georgia State's matchup
zone defense frustrated the Blue Devils.

	   "Right out of the gate we played man defense and they started
posting Beard up and we weren't doing a good job of helping,''
Henry said. "She was getting way too many touches so we
immediately went to a zone. We were trying to make their players
that don't normally take outside shots take them.''

	   But Vicki Krapohl's 3-pointer with 8:25 left gave Duke a 48-37
lead.

	   Georgia State pulled within nine with 4:55 remaining, but
freshman Lindsey Harding helped seal it for the Blue Devils,
stripping Patechia Hartman of the ball and completing a three-point
play that gave Duke a 59-43 lead.

	   Georgia State scored 11 points over the final 12 minutes after
trailing 41-37. Hartman led the way with 16.

	   The Lady Panthers were within six of Tennessee last season at
halftime before losing by 30 in the first round.

	   And once again, Georgia State was in it at the break, down 31-27
to a team that had been ranked No. 1 in the nation for 12 straight
weeks.

	   "I wasn't really shocked because they are a good team,'' said
Iciss Tillis, who added 12 points, six rebounds and three steals
for Duke. "But I had confidence we would pull the game out
somehow. I knew we would get some defensive stops when we needed
them.''
